title: Performs Miracles
text: Having problem cuticles and nails due to nail biting in youth was compounded midlife by medical condition resulting in thin, dry/no luster nails and dry rough cuticles made worse by several years of faux nails.  I've bought and tried numerous hopeful products recommended via internet research several of which helped but not without diligent daily treatments.  Cuccio showed a difference after one application and after a week, I did not recognize my nails and cuticles.  I applied daily the first two weeks but then life took over and I was only applying once or twice a week.  My nails retained the soft luster and my cuticles did not get rough and ragged.  My nails even seem to have slightly thickened which is wonderful as they were tissue thin.  One bottle will last for more than a year as it require only a minute dollop every other nail then massaging it into each nail bed/cuticle.  I will confirm the negative online reviews as to the bottle design; it's dangerous so use it only on a countertop that accomonedates a spillage.  It's well worth the careful attention to bottle placement.

title: OK, I bought this for my wife, but I'll tell you what I know....
text:
She LOVES this!

I mean, I scored such big points buying this, you have no idea!

My wife recently went for a manicure and the person that did her nails told her she needed to use a cuticle oil. Usually that means, order something for me.

So I came on here to Amazon and read a few things, and luckily found this. My wife RAVES about it everyday. She literally thanks me, like I'm the one that made it. She shows me everyday how much better things are and she isn't always complaining, so I got that going for me too.

I did read in a review about a "pen" you put this oil in, so after about 10 days of her using it, I surprised her with a stocking stuffer present of a pack of three pens. It makes putting this stuff on easier and neater.

But don't tell anyone, but I use one of her pens too. This dry weather has been taking a toll on my hands and I have more than normal hang nails. Using this is great.

This has a pleasant smell, and not oily, but I do see why the wife likes it.

The bottle seems to be a great size that for what I see, it should last a long while. The bottle can sit upright, but there is a "dimple" on the side, where you can tilt it too. But the pens are worth looking into.

Two word review: Great Stuff

title: Nice scent, non-greasy, hydrating Cuticle Oil... Weird tingle first 3 applications....
text:
I have been using this oil for about a week and a half. Although I did a test swatch on my arm with no problem, when I put this on my cuticles I felt an odd tingly sensation for the first 3 applications. I could have stopped using it, but I didn't have any swelling or itching -- just an weird tingle -- so I kept applying it once or twice a day. After day 3 the sensation went away. My cuticles are soft and supple and adding the oil doesn't cause a tingle anymore.

I was worried about the Smell based on other reviews. I bought the Pomegranate and Fig just because it was a Prime purchase and was returnable while the Milk and Honey, which was the same price, was listed as non-returnable. I can't speak to the Milk and Honey scent, but the Pomegranate is awesome... slightly sweet but not overpowering at all. This one doesn't feel like it is a good barrier so if you have dry air in your home, don't expect this to work miracles. It helps dry crunchy cuticles in the moment, but wouldn't last overnight or all day as a moisture barrier. Vaseline is better suited for an overnight cuticle treatment in Winter. Overall, this is nice, but to make a difference expect to apply at least morning and night, or more often in Winter or if you wash your hands frequently.

title: Fake synthetic perfume extract
text:
The scent in all of these is horrid because they are using synthetic chemicalized extracts and outright perfume. The scents are terrible because they are not natural and are so strong that they hang around forever; you cannot get rid of the smell! Even after washing your hands thoroughly, even after washing them multiple times, that scent is still there. People sensitive to synthetic fragrances may get a headache from this product. By the way, "extracts" are not natural, even though manufacturers often say that they are. Extracts are processed synthetic perfume products and unhealthy. They cause many people to get headaches.

In addition, this cuticle oil is very greasy and never wants to completely sink in. The ingredients overall are not that great. Several poor quality oils are used, not the better moisturizing ones, and the cottonseed oil is likely GMO (genetically modified) and probably contaminated with pesticide and herbicide residue.

Give this cuticle oil a pass. If you still want to get it anyway, I would recommend only ordering the unscented version! If you want a truly natural one that is fantastic in both ingredients and phenomenal in the way it works (sinks in quickly, moisturizes, healed my cracked thumb corners, natural ingredients with only essential oils for scent), Bee Naturals Nail & Cuticle Oil is the one to get.

title: White Limetta & Aloe Vera
text:
I bought the "White Limetta & Aloe Vera" scent after I debated between a safe scent or a take-a-risk scent. I've got to say that I'm glad i took a chance--I love it! It's different, but delicate and citrusy. It says extract of lime, lemon, and bergamot + aloe juice. I smelled mint in there, instead of bergamot. The oils used are safflower, sunflower, cotton seed, and vegetable, and together, make a smooth, light mix. I rub it all over my hands and into my cuticles. I've not tried it on my body yet, but i don't see why it wouldn't be awesome there! To me, it seems to absorb well... not excessively greasy (I mean, it IS oil, though, so expect a little). Try rubbing it into your skin when it's damp... oil absorbs better, then. Some oils (like avocado, for example) are much thicker and heavier, though, and these aren't like that. Anyway, I really like it and am excited to try the others! Btw, my bottle was a 2.5fl.oz. sphere. I think it's a cool bottle and it will add a nice addition to my glass bottle collection. It would also be great to reuse when I make my own concoctions. I can see why some people are bent out of shape. The dropper doesn't go all the way to the bottom or easily angle when you tilt it to the side. However, if you just put the dropper aside for a second and tilt the bottle far enough, the oil magically pours out of the hole at the top! It's a crazy, new concept!

All said, this is a 5 out of 5 and would recommend for all over body use.

title: Amazing oil for more than just cuticles
text:
This stuff is amazing for more than just cuticles. I love how big the bottle is, and just like others, I was not happy about the odd design, which could lead to the product spilling. I was originally using this just for my cuticles and hands, but recently my elbows became super dry, so I started putting a few drops on my elbows and then followed it with a shea butter cream. After a few days my elbows were back to normal. I am so happy that this product is big enough to use on many areas of the body, and that it really worked for dry elbows, which is something I find is worse than dry cuticles. Awesome product, and totally recommend!
As far as the scent, it is quite neutral. Really, I can barely smell it. I hate perfumed products, and this is more than ok for me. And an amazing thing, I bought this in 2020, and it is now 2022 and the smell is still neutral. It didn't go off, which other oils tend to go off in less than a year.

It‚Äôs far better than hand creams or lotions.  I ordered two more to give away to others.  One last thing to mention is the price is unbelievable.  Truly a win-win-win on all counts. title: OBSESSED - Love this product SO much.
text:
I love how lightweight the oil is but it is still hydrating on my hands. It absorbs really quickly and doesn't feel super oily or leave a oily film/residue and I love how light the fragrance is (I have a fragrance sensitivity so I don't like heavy scented things.)

I get my nails done pretty frequently, more than most I think in the grand scheme of things. I enjoy a fresh set of nails or just a clean manicure/pedicure. My favorite cuticle cream/care before this was Burts Bees lemon butter cuticle cream. It is still my favorite now only for how well it keeps my hands and cuticles healthy looking but also for the smell. But oh my gosh Becky I am completed OBSESSED with this Cuccio oil. I think I spent $9 for the 2.5 fl.oz. bottle and its going to last forever.

I put it on my desk at work with my hand lotion because I work in an office and all the hand washing, typing, paperwork, etc was killer on my hands - lotion alone wasn't cutting it for me, the oil is a nice fast way to get the extra care my hands need without derailing my day for 20-25 minutes while the oil absorbs. I can apply it and rub it in during a call and be done/ready to go by the time I am done so send an email or grab something off the printer.

My first clue should've been the fact that it's called a "cuticle" oil, you'd think a brand that puts out nail care products would know the correct name for the parts of the nail. The ingredients are essentially vegetable oil, which is too large to penetrate skin and nails. After a few days of using this product my skin felt almost plastic-like but then would be super dry really quick, that's because the oil was just sitting on the surface. I'll be sure to read ingredients next time, get yourself a jojoba based blend and see the difference.

text:
UPDATE: I‚Äôve been using this daily for 3 months now, and see zero difference in my nails. And it‚Äôs still a rancid-smelling mess to apply.
ORIGINAL REVIEW: I only just got this, so I can't yet attest to its effectiveness. But the bottle design is terrible:
1. As other reviewers have noted, there is a flat section on the side, near the bottom, that I guess is meant to let you tilt the bottle to get more product out --- but it also makes the bottle unstable and really easy to tip over.
2. It comes with a dropper which releases way too much product & makes for a very messy application -- a brush would be much better for applying over the entire cuticle and nail. I'm going to buy a small empty nail polish bottle with a brush, and decant the oil into it.
Finally, the scent is pretty bad, like rancid coconut. Hopefully I'll get used to it?

title: Smells great, but didn‚Äôt work for me.
text:
Application: I do not recommend using the oil straight out of the bottle. Since the bottle was big and hard to work with, I loaded this cuticle oil into a disposable pen brush for easier application.

Scent: I really love the smell of the milk & honey oil. It can be a little strong if you‚Äôre sensitive to smells.

Effectiveness: For me, this oil is quick to absorb into the skin, and worked really well to moisturize my cuticles at first. However, after a few days of consistent use, I found that it leaves my cuticles drier than before - almost like my cuticles are ‚Äúaddicted‚Äù to the oil. I needed more and more frequent applications of the oil throughout the day to avoid my cuticles drying out.

Overall, I cannot recommend this cuticle oil for everyone. I personally have much better results with a homemade mixture of jojoba oil and vitamin E oil, with a few drops of essential oil mixed in for fragrance. Jojoba oil (which is not an ingredient in the Cuccio oil) is the most similar to the sebum naturally produced by the human skin, and therefore moisturizes very effectively without feeling heavy.

title: Heavenly scent...
text: When I was in high school ( I'm now 62) I had lovely nails. They were strong and grew long. Your would think, now that I'm no longer working, and I use gloves when I clean/ wash dishes, that my nails would thrive, but such is not the case. My nails are literally like onion skin... they peel, are brittle and split... at times down to the quick. I have to cut them so close to the nail bed that they are sore for several days. Yet, last summer, they grew to be the longest in years!!  And for the life of me I can't think of what I did differently. My diet did not change either. I use 'Perfect Formula' clear gel as a base coat, and have for several years.  I take vit. D because I have one kidney. My last resort was to try a cuticle oil, and/or to perhaps try a multivit... or a vit. that is targeted towards nail growth. We'll see what happens with this. It smells and feels divine. It absorbs 'fairly' quickly. It does leave a residue on my phone, I've noticed. But that is not a deal breaker. I'm still trying to guage how much to apply so that it does not drip down my fingers (I've only had this for a couple of days). title: Worsened my cuticles
text: I don‚Äôt usually like to write one star reviews, but this cuticle oil is quite bad. I was looking at all of the positive reviews and thought this would be a nice oil to try particularly for the lower price compared to other cuticle oils. The first night I used it along with Lubriderm lotion to help it absorb, but it did feel a bit greasy. The next morning my hands felt unusually dry. I looked at my cuticles and they also looked dry. Throughout the day, my hands felt drier than usual, and I was using more lotion in between handwashings than I had been before using this oil.  I thought it was due to first time use so I used it again the second night by itself without the lotion and the next morning my cuticles were still dried out and in fact worse with peeling. I then switched to my former Deborah Lippmann cuticle oil to help repair my cuticles, which took about two weeks to get them back to baseline. I went back to look at the one and two star reviews, and the descriptions were the same as my experience. Unfortunately this is not a very effective cuticle oil, and I felt it inappropriate to return it for someone else to use.

The first evening I put this on, I loved the scent and the fairly easy application. You must rub this in to your nailbed and you don‚Äôt need very much oil to do this. Since I‚Äôve only used this a short time, I will need more time to see if this helps permanently. BTW, sometimes I wear gloves after I use the oil.

title: Highly recommended for problem nails
text: As long as I can remember, I have had horrible nails. They have always been thin and split very easily; it was always very embarrassing. As soon as I was old enough, I began going to the salon for acrylics, gels, powder...ugh!  The time and money invested!  Then, I'd get sick of going and peel them off at home (very painful and very bad) and go back to my ugly nails for awhile until I couldn't stand them anymore and begin the cycle again.  Most recently, after peeling them off yet again, I tried "vitamins" guaranteed to make my nails (and hair-added bonus) grow and grow strong! Took them for two months-total waste. Then I tried this. It has done what nothing else could. I massage it in before going to work and before going to bed. It's a little greasy, but I massage it into my hands as a treat for my skin. It smells great and the bottle lasts a long time. I really am impressed. I wish I had a "before" picture to show you so you could see how horrid my nails were, but the after picture isn't bad.

title: Box and the bottle were unsealed!!

The reviews talked about the scent. Either people loved it or they really didn't like it at all. I found it to be neutral. I thought it would smell a bit better, but I like that it's not overwhelming. It doesn't compete with any fragrance that I'm wearing.

I checked many other online sites looking for the best cuticle oil, and this one (the milk and honey formula) kept coming up (in some sites it was the number one choice, and in others, it was up in the top ten).

I've been putting it on my fingers and toes at night before bed and after a shower. I feel that I can notice a difference. It feels good on the bottom of my feet, and it makes them look better, too.

title: I personally found these underwhelming.
text:
I got both the Milk & Honey and Pomegranate & Fig scents.

The good: This is a pretty large bottle for a pretty great price. So, even if you end up not liking it, you will not have laid out a lot of money for it (and cuticle oils can get pretty expensive.)

The meh: I am really not a fan of either scent. Lots of other reviews rave about the scent, but they both smell a little cheap and artificial to me (and I am not a person who is picky about making sure her products only use natural scents. Like, one of my favorite lotions is OPI's Coconut Melon Avojuice lotion, and it is not something I'd describe as natural-smelling, just well-executed.) However, I do not find either scent overpowering or truly offensive, and scent preferences are pretty subjective. So, unless you are particularly sensitive to fragrances, you'll probably be able to manage, even if you don't love the fragrance.

Additionally, these products use a dropper, not a brush. I prefer a brush, especially in order to be able to apply to the underside of the free edge (the part that extends past your actual finger, which is crucial, especially if you are wearing polish.) With these, I have to try to drop a teeny bit under each one, which is still too much while not actually getting the entire underside, and it just kind of pools in the area where the nail and finger meet. With a brush, I can control the amount of oil much better, and get the entire underside. Although, Amazon does sell refillable oil brushes that you could use for this purpose; it will just make the one thing this product really has going for it (an attractive price point) a little less attractive. I guess you could also use a nail art brush, but I feel like unless you have a specific, dust-free place to keep it and/or you are diligent about cleaning it, then it will get dirty/grimy awfully quickly, or get nail oil all over your other stuff (and it overall detracts from the "ease of use" factor. Every other dedicated nail/cuticle oil I have ever used had a brush.)

Not exactly bad, but sub-meh: None of the oils in this cuticle oil (safflower, sunflower, cotton seed, vegetable) are *particularly* well-known for their moisturizing properties, although a naturally, plant-derived oil will be moisturizing to some degree. Some people absolutely swear by jojoba-based cuticle oils; presumably, it is the *most* like skin's natural oil, and is supposed to absorb best. Supposedly, there is some science to back this up, but the biggest proponent of this science is also someone who makes a cuticle oil. It's a good product that I have used and liked, but it is on the expensive side. Still, I personally have good luck with a blend of jojoba/vitamin E oils; I find it does absorb quickly, whereas these Cuccio oils just kind of sit on my fingers (even after massaging it into my nails and cuticles) and I find I have to wipe some off (although some of this might be related to the over-application that just kind of naturally happens because of the dropper delivery mechanism.) I also do not feel these oils moisturize quite as well as the jojoba-based oils I use. However, your own personal body chemistry also plays a role here, so you may find jojoba a bad choice for you, and this oil blend a great choice for you.

At the end of the day, if you are looking for something to try to help parched cuticles, but don't need to care about making sure it "absorbs into your nails," or you're just starting to get into nail care and don't want to spend a small fortune, this oil might be worth a try for you. Especially if you are diligent about using it regularly, several times a day, and actually massaging it in - a good deal of the nail-growing benefit comes from the massaging your cuticles/nail beds, which helps stimulate circulation/new cell growth (as well as just kind of generally making you mindful of your nails overall, which will in turn make you more careful of how you use your hands and less likely to do things like popping open cans of soda, or using your nails as tools, or other things that lead to breaks.) But, personally, I have other oils I would recommend over this brand (not the least of which is a big old bottle of jojoba oil with a little vitamin E oil thrown in - fragrance-free, so it won't overpower, or interfere with your favorite lotion, and if you buy the 4oz size, can be had as cheaply as $10 or so; while you might also have to get some Vitamin E oil and a brush pen, you only use a little of the Vitamin E, and the bursh pens are reusable, so both will last through several bottles of jojoba oil, and so the total cost is on par, if not cheaper, than these products.)

title: It's a NO from me
text:
I bought this product despite reading some bad reviews because I thought to myself "I'm not a picky person, can cuticle oil REALLY be 'bad'?"
Well my friends, the answer to that self monologue is yes, yes cuticle oil can, in fact, be bad. The smell is terrible and it's not very thick. I can't see myself using this because the smell just bothers me that much, so it's pretty much a waste of the 8 to 10 bucks I paid for it. If you're remotely sensitive to smells, don't buy this... You'll end up with yet another product in your house you never use but feel too guilty to throw away and wouldn't be so mean to gift away, so you'll be stuck with it til one day you have a big enough pile of stuff you never use and the anxiety that it causes outweighs the guilt you feel about throwing any of it away so you you quickly, like a madwoman throw it all in a big, extra thick trash bag with the year's pile of junk mail and weeks old leftover take out you never touched and promise yourself this will be the last time because you'll stop buying things that suck.

Sorry for the long review and most likely really lame attempt at comedy, but this one really triggered me.

title: This oil is rad!
text:
Honestly, for a budget cuticle oil, this stuff SLAPS. It's not super quick to soak in like some other cuticle-specific oils, but the price makes it all worth it. It's getting to be winter in the Midwest and my cuticles suffer in dry air. They split and tear and it's incredibly painful. So far, this oil has completely taken care of them!
As someone mentioned, the Milk & Honey scent smells identical to the Softsoap liquid soap of the same variety but it's kind of nostalgic in a way for me. It goes away quickly, too. I use it multiple times a day when it's dry.
It takes about 10 minutes to dry. I'm usually working on my computer, so I often get grease all over it because I'm impatient, but that's my fault. It's not sticky and the smell isn't overpowering. Keep in mind that the bottle does have a notch in it so it can fall over if you don't have it propped against something while it's open or you're a klutz like me.
This has helped my nails grow and kept my cuticles nice and soft! 100% worth it!

title: Nice quality nail oil
text: I used NutraNail for many years, and hadn't found a nail oil that moisturized as well until now. I will need to update once I've tested it on a high shine buff. Only NutraNail kept the shine, others dulled my painstaking work, we'll see how this stacks up! White Limetta is a light clean scent. I bought a nail oil brush pen for easier, targeted application. A little goes a long way. Don't be shy, use it often! My cuticles are much less dry after hand washing. Use on cuticles, over and under the tips of your nails. It does absorb into unpainted nails, rather than just sitting on top unlike others I have tried. If you are a nail biter, supposedly safer than NutraNail. I'm not a nail bitter, and if you do, stop that! :)

title: Read Before Buying
text:
I have very hard well water so my cuticles and skin around my nails are extremely dry and flaky. I was hoping that putting this cuticle oil on before going to bed would moisturize my cuticle area. Unfortunately, as soon as my hands are exposed to my well water the next day, my cuticles are literally dry and flaky again. Desperate I tried NOW pure lanolin on my cuticle area before going to bed. After four days of using this lanolin my cuticle area is soft with no flakiness. For my money I will never purchase cuticle oil again but pure lanolin instead. It withstands my hard water and my cuticle area stays soft with minimal to no flakiness.

Bottom line: This cuticle oil works great for most people but for those of us who have hard water I'd recommend NOW pure lanolin instead.

title: Easy to apply & moisturizes my cuticles
text: Winter in the upper mid-west can be brutal on your skin. The air is dry, cold and I find that I'm washing my hands more than usual. All equals the perfect storm for dried out skin, especially around my nails. Lotion and hand cream alone just wasn't cutting it. When I was younger I remember my grandmother using cuticle oil from Mary-kay to rub on her fingers every evening. I found a tiny bottle of nail & cuticle oil at the local drug store. It worked okay, but expensive for only 5ml. I found this oil and read some of the reviews, decided to give it a try. I have been very happy with the results. Not only are my cuticles soft, but so is the skin around my nails. The scent is light and the oil absorbs in quickly (20-25 min.), the little hand/finger massage is a nice relaxing bonus. I can't say that this oil is better than any other kind on the market, but I can tell you that the amount you get (75ml) is worth the cost.

title: Non-Absorbing Scented Oil
text:
Pros: Cheap, Smells Good

Cons: Everything Else

Not sure if I just got a bad batch or what but this oil does not absorb at all. Just sits on your fingers forever. Their instructions state one drop per cuticle, which by the way, is WAYYY too much (you'll have oil all over your hands). 2-3 drops per HAND is sufficient. They also state to rub it in, we'll rubbing does nothing but spread it around as it never absorbs. I rubbed, let set, and rubbed multiple times then waited up to 45 minutes. No change in absorption, just shiny oily fingers. Mixing it in with hand lotion seemed to help considerably but probably defeats the purpose.

Second, the bottle has a slant on the bottom which makes it unstable. If you even look at it wrong, it'll tip over. What is even the point of this slant? Just make a normal bottle.

However, I will say this oil smells amazing. Not sure what use I'll have with that alone but good job on this point.

But you get what you pay for. Not sure what all these 5 star reviews are ranting on about as I had literally the opposite results. Also keep in mind, many reviews are showing an allergic reaction so be wary.

Ingredients (seems to be mostly various forms of vegetable oil)
-Carthamus Tinctorius Oil (Safflower Seed Oil // Vegetable Oil)
-Helianthus (Sunflower)
-Annuus Seed Oil (Sunflower Seed Oil // Vegetable Oil)
-Gossypium Herbaceum Seed Oil (Cotton Seed Oil)
-Olus Oil (Vegetable Oil)
-Milk Extract
-Mel Extract (Extracted from Honey)
-Fragrance
-Tocopheryl Acetate (Vitamen E Acetate)
-Tocopherol (Vitamen E // Derived from Vegetable Oil)

text: So - I hate to be the critic but I have to be honest. This cuticle oil did NOTHING for me. It smells wonderful and the bottle looks good. BUT the cap cracked shortly after purchasing, the oil feels good on the skin but it just doesn‚Äôt absorb enough into the skin or nail and actually made my skin drier than usual. Water alone was more moisturizing! My nails have dry cracks running through them 5 minutes after applying, like I put nothing on! I unfortunately followed the hype of this product because of the reviews - but the ingredients are not very good for the intentions of the product. Safflower oil, sunflower oil are oils that just SIT on the skin. They DO NOT penetrate. No wonder! I am to blame for not doing my research on the ingredient list prior to buying but this company proves that flooding reviews and good marketing go a very long way.

title: This product is amazing!
text:
In the 20 or so years I've been shopping on Amazon this is only my second or third product review. I just had to write one for this amazing oil.
I wore the polish on my toenails way too long and when it was removed I had large white patches on every nail, especially on the big toes. I was told the patches were caused by dehydration and to not wear polish for three weeks or longer. I was also told to use cuticle oil on the nails to rehydrate them. I was using a cuticle oil and then a cuticle cream I had on hand. The patches were not improving.
Then I ordered the Milk & Honey Cuticle Revitalizing Oil. Amazing! Upon first application the white patches disappeared. Disappeared. No exaggeration!
I am continuing to use the Milk & Honey Oil even though the patches are gone. In a few weeks I will start wearing polish on my toenails again, but I will never be without this product.

title: Works but smells funny
text:
My hands tend to be on the drier side, especially around my cuticles, and I have a small patch of stubbornly dry, slightly thicker skin on one of my thumbs. I've only used this oil for about two days, but I'm already noticing that it's become a bit softer, and the dry spot is staying away! I've been applying it after every "harsh" wash like doing dishes, touching laundry soap, after shower. It does leave lightly oily residue, but I just wipe my palms and fingertips off and it's fine.

I bought the pomegranate fig scent because of all the reviews saying they love it...it gets an "eh" from me. It's floral but has this chemically smell, almost like a super faint nail polish remover? As reference, I dislike strong scents, and my favored profiles are usually light fruity or citrus.

5/5 for effectiveness
3/5 for scent

title: Great Product.
text:
This is the best oil I've used. Better than OPI, but I was never impressed with theirs in the first place. Very moisturizing. Soaks right in. If you put it all the way around rather than just dropping it, like the whole cuticle and around the nail, which I do, because my skin gets dry there, you can just leave it be, without massaging it in or anything. This works best if you wash your hands first to let your skin suck up the moisture, but most people know this.

Love the smell. The scent is like the that one liquid soap in the milk and honey scent, as someone else mentioned. I can't think of the brand offhand.

Not sure what everyone's problem is with the packaging. The bottle is huge. I like how there is a flat spot on the side to tilt it. If it gets knocked, it falls on the the side rather than falling over. Dropper seals tight. I can turn it upside down. No leaks.

I don't know if it strengthens the nails. I have a genetic disorder. I have acrylics on my hands, or they would rip so bad I would bleed because they are so soft.
Basically, they are a like babies nails. My toes are not much better. Stupid soft, so I have to keep them super short, and nothing has ever helped. If the oil does something, I will be amazed, and will be sure to update.

title: Use on your NAILS!  game changer
text:
I always thought that cuticle oil was for cuticles. I'm not sure when or where, but I figured out that you should really be slathering all over your nail area. My weak, fragile, constantly breaking fingernails and toenails seemed like a lost cause. This oil is amazing. Almost unscented. I use the dropper to drop it on all of my fingers and then rub the oil in over entire nail. My nails immediately stopped breaking. WHAT?! One of the many things I wish I knew when I was younger.
This oil is great, and it is very affordable! I love this stuff. I bought several more bottles so I can have them at work, next to bed, etc. Since I'm forgetful to use things like this, I figure that this affordable stuff is worth stocking in several places so I have it when I remember to use it. :)

title: Can't find anything wrong
text:
- MOISTURIZING: I have been putting this cuticle oil on every day now for about a week and it's been great so far! Quick-drying, but still moisturizing.

- DROPPER: I saw other people having issues with the dropper and granted, I've only been using a week, but it's been sturdy. Being this is a personal cuticle oil and I'm not using on others, I really don't need to squeeze the dropper to get the amount of oil needed for my tiny cuticles anyway; I just place the droppers end on my cuticle and the right amount of oil is distributed once I lift.

- SCENT: The scent is not overwhelming, but it's definitely there--in a good way for sure.

- PACKAGING: The package arrived extra bubble wrapped, so there was caution when mailed over. The item itself in appearance is round in shape and in a glass container with a glass dropper. The super cool (to me) thing that wasn't mentioned in the description is that you can stand the bottle on a flat surface in two different ways. One way is the obvious upright and the other is at an angle or tilted to the side. I'm assuming this feature is for when you start to run low because mine is still full and I can't tilt it without spilling some of the oil.

- So much oil, I don't think I'll ever run out (2.5 fl oz / 75 mL)

title: Great oil!
text:
I have been neglecting my cuticles for long enough, I feel like my hands never look "clean" because of the rough cuticles. So I decided to buy this and set it next to me on my nightstand as a nightly reminder to moisturize before going to bed. I am following through as much as I can (still horrible at doing it daily) but I do notice a significant difference when I use this. Before I was using argan oil or any other lotion, and while with these I saw an immediate difference, the softness would go away after I washed the area. This oil actually makes a difference, and its even better when Im actually consistent with it. I still pair with a lotion.

The one thing I dont like: the scent. I think this is very personal but I am particularly not a fan of the sweet honey smell. I've grown to tolerate it because of how good the product is (and you seriously cannot beat the price when compared against other cuticle oils) but I would even rather it was unscented.

title: Amazing: fast and effective
text:
I have tried so many lotions and moisturizers for my dry and unsightly cuticles, and this is The One. It immediately soothes my cuticles, so that they recede to near invisibility. Mission accomplished.

I have only been using this product for a few days, so am unsure of the long term results. I suspect that it is only effective while it is present, and that it isn't doing any actual healing. But I am not tempted to get out the cuticle clippers, so that is probably a good thing long term.

There have been comments about applying the oil with the dropper. It does take a little practice -- just touch each cuticle with the dropper, leaving a tiny drop. The oil spreads itself. I think it's a huge advantage that you don't have to get your fingertips all oily when applying it.

I have also noticed that this oil is not undermining my nail polish.

I am just very pleased with this product. At this rate, this bottle is going to last forever.

title: Eh, not bad but not enough hydration
text:
As cuticle oils go, this one isn't horrible. It does help some with dry cuticles, but you need to reapply after every hand washing as it doesn't last through soap and water. The dropper opening lets out a big drop of oil that's more than enough for each nail bed. A smaller dropper opening might have been better for more control over the product. The bottle I chose is fragrance-free, though it still has a faint oil scent. Nothing terrible, though. I like that it doesn't have such a strong smell that it affects anything I eat or drink anytime my hand gets near my nose. Bottle closes securely and doesn't leak if knocked over. A little pricey even for the large amount you get.

This cuticle oil from Cuccio isn't bad. I can't really give it more than three stars as it didn't really do much to improve the dry, raggedy cuticles on my hands and feet. Applying copious amounts didn't make a difference, neither did doing so frequently. Thankfully this oil absorbs quickly and didn't leave my nails a greasy mess. Actually, it's almost as if this oil isn't oily enough, if that makes sense. The consistency is thin - thinner than most other cuticle oils I've tried out in the past, like there is too much water in the formula. I can see this being a good option if you have cuticles that are already in good condition as a way to maintain them. I ended up finishing off the bottle by adding this to my heavy duty winter body butter as a way to up the hydration, and when used this way I did see a difference. Unfortunately, this oil doesn't pack enough of a punch to tackle my horribly dry cuticles.

title: A perfect oil to keep your nails in great shape.
text: This oil is a must have for keeping your cuticles and nails in tip top shape. I recently started wearing acrylic on my nails, and it's amazing how fast your nails and cuticles can dry out. I usually just put the oil on at night before bed. It dispenses great from the dropper, one drop at a time. I put it on the top of the nail in the middle of the cuticle and then work it in. I found it flows around and coats the back of the nail without any effort. I can tell if I've gone a day without using the oil! It absorbs well and softens the skin, cuticle, and I think it also helps my nails. They are not brittle and I've had no problem with the acrylic. After getting the acrylic put on, I read up on the upkeep. Many sites said  if you keep your nails supple, they are able to bend and take more pressure. I believe this to be true. The combination of oils are great and really good for you. The oil, milk & honey scent is very enjoyable. It is not overpowering, very subtle, but I found it to be more on the sweet side.

title: Affordable, smells and works great!!
text:
After a lifetime of nail biting and presson, acrylics, nextgen, and gel, my nails were brittle, thin, ridgy, and unhealthy. I‚Äôm a SAHM and my hands are always in water or cleaning products. I never took care of my cuticles and rarely got a manicure because the polish chipped within a day and I would start biting. It was a waste of time, money, and effort.
My friend began selling a polish product which didn‚Äôt chip and lasted more than a week, so I finally stopped biting my nails. I started to take care of my nails but they were still very weak and would tear as soon as I removed the polish product, so I looked for a cuticle oil to help.
I remembered seeing this oil a couple of years ago at a salon and thought the price was really good for the amount you get. Let me tell you... this stuff is AMAZING! My 10 year old daughter, who has always taken great care of her nails, decided to ditch her solar oil and now shares my Cuccio milk and honey oil! We LOVE the scent which is light and a little sweet, like honey. It reminds me of burts bees baby bee bath products. It conditions so incredibly well and my nails seem three times stronger after two weeks of daily use. We have not had any problems with the bottle or dropper. I wish I had a before photo of my nails but I was too embarrassed to take one. I am posting a pic of my current nails with the Cuccio bottle; 5 weeks post biting and two weeks of Cuccio cuticle oil use.

text: This is just what I was looking for! Even though I have oily skin, my cuticles get dry from time to time, and I never had anything that could help me until now! I use it at night mostly, and once I put it on, I rub it into my cuticles and my fingers do not stay oily for too long which I like. I have noticed a difference in my cuticles in just the 12 days that I have been using it. I don‚Äôt know if my nails are growing faster because I have not used it for that long, but I have noticed that my nails are a bit more flexible, but it could be a placebo effect. title: Great healing cuticle oil
text:
I'm terribly hard on my hands, and my fingers always have hang nails, flaky skin around the sides of my nails, and horrible looking cuticles.

I bought this cuticle oil, applied it once, and promptly forgot I was going to try to do better for my hands... for an entire week. You'd think it would be running across the bottle that would remind me of my mission to improve my habits, but it wasn't. What it took was me suddenly noticing that my fingers looked 100% better. No dry skin, no hang nails, who's hands are these anyway? Surely not mine!

All I can say is that somehow applying this stuff once in a week and going about my business as usual, washing dishes, working with power tools, doing yard work, and just living my usual life somehow worked. I know this sounds preposterous, I wouldn't believe it myself if I wasn't looking at my own hands!

Bonus: it smells great! Let's be honest, it works so well that it could smell like hot garbage and I'd still use it. What did they put in this stuff, unicorn spit? Something magical, certainly.

title: Moisturizing Nail Oil
text:
I started using nail polish more and more frequently, and I found that my nails were becoming a little bit dry. So, I started researching nail oil, and after reading lots of reviews, I eventually settled on Cuccio.
First of all, it smells wonderful. Smell is very important to me, and I was very pleased by the milk and honey scent. I don‚Äôt find it too greasy. I just put a drop on each nail, rub it in, then wipe the excess oil off my skin and go about whatever I was doing. If my nails are particularly dry, I usually just watch TV and let it sit on my nails for 15 or 20 minutes, and I can really tell a difference. My nails are shinier and just seem more neat and healthier.
Also, this bottle is BIG. I unfortunately wasn‚Äôt paying attention and knocked the bottle off my desk when it was open. I spilled more than half of the brand new bottle. However, even after using a drop on each nail, more than once a day for a bit over a month, I realized the remainder of the bottle will last me a long time. Overall, I am very pleased with this nail oil and will definitely buy more whenever I run out.

title: Fine for basic nail care but nothing more
text:
As an oil, it‚Äôs pretty messy, and you actually only need about half a drop per nail in my experience. The dropper sort of ‚Äúleaks‚Äù oil, so I just dab the end of the dropper on each nail as opposed to squeezing the dropper from the top. In other words, there‚Äôs enough oil on the tip of the dropper to cover all my cuticles in one go. I suppose that could be a plus in terms of making the product last longer, but to me it seems like a product design error.

After I apply the oil to my cuticles, I spend a few minutes massaging into my cuticles. I also spread it outward a bit, onto the nail and the tip of my fingers/toes, since there is so much product to work with (and I have pretty small nails).

It takes about 20-30 minutes to fully absorb. Sometimes I will apply a moisturizer afterward, and that seems to help ‚Äúset‚Äù everything and make the oil absorb more quickly. This is currently my preferred method, since it leaves my hands/feet feeling the most moisturized. However, I think this product works best as part of a normal nail care routine, versus a treatment for dry/damaged nails, which is what I was hoping for.

The smell is okay. It‚Äôs not bad, but it doesn‚Äôt smell like a natural honey scent. It‚Äôs more like something you would get at Bath & Body Works in that it ‚Äúmimics‚Äù a scent. However, it‚Äôs light enough to smell pleasant and does not overwhelm me or give me a headache.

Overall, good product for the price, but I will be looking into purchasing a more high-end product that has more potency.

title: Healthy nail bed, hello!
text: I am very satisfied with this cuticle oil. I'm always getting my nails done and like to keep up on my nail bed because my hands tend to get very dry, causing my cuticles to tear. The scent is not overpowering at all, lightly floral and honey based. The oil absorbs quite well with no residue. Very moisturizing and over time makes it easier to manage my cuticles. I also picked up a cuticle cutter which seems to be alot easier when this oil has been applied. I highly recommend this product. Also a great price point for anyone that wants to take care of there cuticles at home vs waiting for the salon. For anyone complaining about the bottle shape, I disagree with the negative reviews. I think it's a very cute design. I understand that I have to hold it when putting the top back in and that doesn't bother me at all. If you're rushing on the other hand and don't take care, you'll end up spilling it so maybe others should consider getting something easier to manage?? Overall, I'm happy.

title: Perfect Product
text:
I used to be a nail biter, so I'm incredibly happy with how much I've let my nails grow. However, they're extremely weak, brittle, and thin (enough that I can easily bend the nail back and forth). I got this oil in hopes to eventually strengthen my nail and the skin/cuticle (since I also used to pick at that).

So far I'm very content with the results. The picture of my nails was taken about 5-10 minutes after applying the oil and they look and feel wonderful. The oil itself smells really nice, though it is a little strong and you might smell it for up to an hour after putting it on (as time goes on though it gets fainter). I got the Pomegranate & Fig oil, and the smell reminds me of being on a tropical beach with flowers and fruit.

I was also surprised with the size (considering how cheap it was), because you don't need a lot (of oil) to moisturize your nails/cuticles. A little goes a long way, and a small pin-sized droplet on each nail was enough to cover the nail and the cuticle, as well as the nails and cuticles on my other hand (basically I rubbed the oil on one hand then rubbed my nails/hands together to do my other hand).

I don't really have any complaints, but I will say that if you put too much on, your fingers/hand will feel a bit greasy and you'll have to wash them if you plan on doing anything. The times I accidentally put on too much, I just let them sit and soak up as much oil as possible, then gently rinsed my hands and I was good to go, and my hands still felt nice and moisturized.

title: Works wonders!
text:
I purchased this Cuccio Cuticle Oil on September 25th and received it 6 days later on October 1st. I've been using this cuticle oil for over a month and a half and feel that it has helped my hands look much nicer! It has a pleasant light floral scent and a dry but moisturizing texture that settles nicely into the skin. I put this oil onto my cuticles every morning and use Jergen's lotion over it to add more moisture and seal in the oils. It has significantly improved the appearance of my very dry winter hands and has my cuticles looking much more pink and less jagged!

You barely have to use any of the product to nourish all 10 fingers so the price-point is excellent! title: Fairy Tale Ending
text:
I was struggling with dry, brittle and shedding nails for the past 2 years. It was upsetting because I had very strong, beautiful nails all of my life, people used to think I had wraps of gel manicures but they were my nails with a $10 mani. However, about 2 years ago I stopped going to the salon to get my weekly manicures because I was not happy with all the chemicals I was being exposed to, so I decided to start doing my own nails using organic, 10-free (low toxic) nail products. Long story short, it was not a seamless transition. I tried all of the nail strengthens that were supposed to be awesome, again low toxic and nothing worked. I thought, oh well, I just have to live with these horrible nails now unless I go back to chemicals...no way!

One day I decided to try a good cuticle oil, I remember the shop owner of my nail salon mentioning how important cuticle oil is for your nails. This product received such rave reviews I thought, why not? Fairy tale ending...I got my beautiful strong nails back! I am so grateful I tried this product! It smells wonderful and it has really healed my nails. I use it on my nails in the morning and it he evening before I go to bed, I have very dry skin.
It only took a few days to see the difference and after three weeks, they are lovely!

title: The best ever. Better than prescription ointments.
text:
Stop. Don‚Äôt look any further for a cuticle oil. This stuff is amazing.

My nails have been crap my entire life. I was 45 years old with crap nails. The thumb nails were deeply ridged beyond anything I‚Äôve ever seen on another human in real life. If you search lichen planus if the nails - that‚Äôs what my thumbs looks like. Deep horizontal grooves. They were also quickly becoming spoon nails. I tried everything. I tried prescription steroid ointments nightly covered by a bandaid and finger cot. Minimal improvement at best. Solar oil helped and I did use it for a long time. Then, I saw this on amazon and ordered yet another product in desperation. It was cheap and I had little to lose.

This oil has transformed my nails. I‚Äôve been using it regularly for a month and have seen tremendous improvement. My nails aren‚Äôt perfect but the grooves have actually filled back in and the spoon shape is flattening.

I use this probably three times per day. I carry it with me. I put it on at my desk, I use it at night, pretty much any time I see and think to put it on. It has made a tremendous difference, not just in my thumb nails but in all my nails and cuticles, which were always ragged and often painful.

I can‚Äôt say enough about this product. It lasts a long time, too. I just ordered another bottle along with refillable oil pens so I can stop carrying around the big bottle. I plan to use this forever.

If you have hopeless nails and cuticles, please give this a try. I wish I had found this years ago.

I know this is supposed to be for cuticles, but I use on my feet to soften my calluses as well. It works wonders for both.

I recently had a visit to the orthopedic, and much to my dismay, the two most handsome doctors walked in the room. (Think Italian cologne model gorgeous).

I had an ankle injury, and at this point, my feet were swollen, tired and stinky. I also need a fresh coat of polish. However, thanks to the oil, my cuticles were flawless and my feet were so soft because I apply it every night before I go to bed. It was my only saving grace in the most uncomfortable appointment I ever experienced.

Needless to say, I highly recommend it. I add a few drops and let it absorb, and then proceed with my foot cream.

title: Nails & cuticles look so much better!
text:
First time using cuticle oil and it's made a big difference in how my fingernails look. They also don't feel so brittle. I've been using this oil every night for about a week and my cuticles are no longer looking so raggedy. I usually have painful hangnails but I no longer do.

The first night I soaked my nails in water with soap (anyone old enough to remember Madge & Palmolive? ;) ) then used this cuticle pusher : Ceramic Pusher File - https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0862DL7G8?psc=1&ref=ppx_yo2ov_dt_b_product_details ,carefully trimmed of the dead cuticle and applied the oil. Then applied the oil every night since. I no longer have painful hangnails and my nails look healthy with a little bit of glow to them. Definitely satisfied with my purchase.

title: Everything you need to take care of your fingers in a bottle :)
text:
Before I requested this product, me being me, I was skeptical about all too good to be true claims made on this product page detail. But then again, I thought 82% 5 star ratings out of almost 100,000 reviews couldn‚Äôt be that bad. Well, now I am one of those 82% haha.
I have been using this oil on my nails and fingers that get extremely dry during winter for over a week now. I put a generous amount of oil all over my hands right before I go to sleep, and put a little around my nail and cuticle after taking a showering in the morning. I like that this oil isn‚Äôt too heavy nor sticky, rather a bit watery like light oil. And I have been enjoying how this oil made my fingers and nails feel so far! Of course, I will have to wait a bit longer to comment on its effectiveness with more conviction, but temporary results have been good !
It looks like there are many cheaper options on Amazon, but I think everything should be evaluated in terms of quality (performance) vs price. For me, (not having used many oils particularly made for nails), the cost performance of this oil seems quite decent!

title: Artificially Scented, But Has Vitamin E to Moisturize
text:
First off, I've never had a cuticle oil a day in my life; I was told to try some to help with my dry cuticles after the winter, so I ordered this product. It was the best value I found on Amazon. I've had this product for three days, and I had split cuticles. After twice daily application, my cuticles are completely healed. I rub this product into my nails as well, as they're very brittle and tend to break and split apart easily. My nails seem stronger than they did, and they tend to dry faster than my cuticles do.

This product smells artificially scented, but it is an EXCELLENT SCENT. For the price, it seems to be one of the best deals on a cuticle oil. Definite warning, though, for those looking for "natural, organic" things--this product is not made from milk and honey. It doesn't have jojoba in it; it does have synthetic scent to it. However, it does have Vitamin E, which has been known to help moisturize cuticles for a long time.

I recommend this product to all but those who are looking for natural, organic things. It smells good, and does a good job speeding the healing process on damaged cuticles.

title: Absolutely wonderful!
text:
So far this cuticle oil has been proven more effective than other oils simply because the smell is so good, I am encouraged to use it more often. :D Seriously, words can't describe how good the smell of Pomegranate and Fig is! I am willing to sniff it 24/7!
I wish it'd make sense to order the Milk and Honey, too, but it doesn't. The bottle is unexpectedly huge (75ml or 2.5 fl. oz.), meaning it will last me forever. It absorbs well and quickly. The bottle is made of robust plastic, which is also a plus for a clumsy gal such as myself, who drops things left and right.

And more importantly it does its job - keeps the cuticles moist, flexible and minimal and makes my manicure look tidy for a long time. Thankfully, I don't have much going in terms of cuticle growth, but still needed to clean them up once a week give or take. Now after I started using Cuccio Apple Cuticle Remover combined with this oil, I am three weeks in and there's nothing to tend, other than occasionally pushing the cuticles back.

The only and really minor detail I am not satisfied with 100% is the applicator. I suppose, if it's intended to be used by multiple people, the dropper is the reasonable and the hygienic option. But for personal use I'd rather have a brush, since that's how I use the dropper anyway. So I'll probably transfer the product into a cuticle pen at some point. But that's really nitpicking on my part. Not worth quarter of a star.

title: Amazing Scents Not Always Winners
text:
Following positive reviews and a recommendation from a nail tech, I purchased this Cuccio Revitalizing Cuticle Oil in the Milk & Honey scent. Happily, the product arrived quickly and in perfect condition! Sadly, it didn't moisturize as well as I'd hoped.

I turned to this product after finishing a bottle of another popular brand (starts with a D, end in an i), which I really liked, though not the price tag.
As mentioned, after recommendations, I hoped this would be a great alternative, but was disappointed. Over time - I used it for about 3 months - I noticed that my cuticles just weren't looking or feeling as moisturized as previously, with another product. No other changes to skincare regimen.

Pros:
+ Delicious scent
+ Great bottle with dropper applicator - love that the bottle can sit straight up or tilt
+ Good price for amount of product

Cons:
- Found it to be less moisturizing than another previously used product
- Becausemy skin was responding negatively & cuticle care is important to me, I had to switch to something more moisturizing for my skin

title: EXCELLENT!!!!
text:
I got this today (milk and honey) and I had to try it. It's amazing! I use gel polish and I'm hard on my hands and don't always remember to wear gloves. From doing dishes by hand, bathing dogs, doing yard work, and taking care of 2 little babies... sometimes gloves don't even cross my mind. Immediately after using this, my cuticles and finger tips look healthy and hydrated. The oil absorbs fairly quick, but my cuticles and sides of my nails were most likely that dried out. My toe nails also look amazing now.
As others have said, a little of this goes a long way. I didn't squeeze the topper. I just lightly touched the end to my cuticles to get a little drop on each finger and then massaged it in. It's also not strong smelling. Just a nice light scent. Certain strong smells can give me a headache. I also have sensitive skin and have broken out in hives over different lotions and soaps. This is perfect.
I know what I'm getting my mom and sisters (my best friends are family to me) for gifts. It also helps that there's scents everyone I know will love. I got the milk and honey for myself.
